SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday, May 14th, 2021 client received her first dose of Pfizer COVID vaccine to left deltoid (LOT # EW0182, EXP 5/15/21) at approximately 11:04 AM. Pt verbalized the only medication she is on is hormonal birth control, and has a history of a Penicillin allergy, no further allergies or conditions indicated. After receiving the vaccine, the client told RN that she has a history of anxiety and syncopy after blood draws. Pt sat at the vaccine station and stated she was feeling very weak and anxious. Co-lead RN  and Lead RN  noticed pt across the room and went to assess around 11:10. Upon observation, pt looked pale in color and had cool, clammy skin. While at vaccine station, pt had small emesis x2 at 11:12 am. At 11:10 am vitals were taken by EMT : BP: 126/89, HR: 99, O2: 100%. Client was escorted to the zero-gravity chair and was given a bottle of water and Gatorade. Upon assessment by EMTs  client's last meal was cereal at 09:00 am. At 11:35 am vitals were taken: BP: 88/74, Hr: 77, RR: 16, O2 sat: 99%, with a strong radial pulse.  Immediately after, Co-Lead RN  offered pt chips as pt had no further episodes of emesis. Pt sat in zero-gravity chair eating chips and vitals were taken again at 11:55 am, BP: 88/78, HR: 79, RR: 20, and O2: 98%. At that time pt stated that she was ?feeling much better?. At 12:05 pm, final vitals were taken, BP: 95/65, HR: 74, RR: 20, O2: 98%. Patient was alert and oriented x4 during entire interaction. No further interventions indicated. Pt was educated by Co-Lead RN  and Lead RN  on signs and symptoms of adverse reactions and when to go to the ED/call MD. Pt was able to ambulate with her brother-in-law to her car unassisted with a steady gait at approximately 12:07 pm.
Difficulty breathing,  dizziness, ear pounding

ALLERGIES: Medication ALLERGIES:: Topamax Penicillin Ambien Septra Bicillin Vicodin Oxycodone

My adverse reaction began at 1:00 am on 5/14/2021. I had experienced body aches earlier in the evening, but at 1:00 I awoke with a fever of 101.2, severe body aches, extreme thirst despite drinking a lot of water earlier in the evening. This fever persisted until 6:00 am this morning, 5/15/2021. The body aches are persisting, however have diminished. There was not a time in more than 36 hours that my temp was under 101.2, the highest reading being 101.8.  This fever was accompanied by nausea, headache, severe body aches and nearly constant shivering.   I have been a Registered Nurse for 37 years, and I am a very healthy individual. I have none of the co-morbidities that are related to Covid-19. I am utterly appalled that people are not being advised, or warned about the possible side effects of this vaccine. If any other medication on the market carried the possibility of this type of side effect, and patients were not being warned, there would be lawsuits happening everywhere.   I would like to know the rate at which reactions like the one I've experienced are occuring.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Adverse event: RN called to vehicle by father who was yelling for help. Once RN arrived at vehicle opened passenger door to find patient fluttering eyes after father stated he had just passed out. Patient was clammy, pale, and diaphoretic. RN advised patient to take slow deep breaths. Patient followed instructions, stated his name and said he felt 'funny'. Pulse taken and was HR 58. Then vehicle was moved to the side and vital signs were taken at 1301. BP 82/42, HR 80,  RR 13. Patient was alert, oriented and answered questions appropriately.   Treatments:  RN and Charge RN present and spoke to both Father and patient about potential contributing factors to episode. Patient given water and gatorade. Able to finish bottle of gatorade and stated his symptoms had improved. Second set of vitals taken at 1324. BP 116/72, HR 82, RR 16. Patient also stated he had a banana for breakfast. Advised patient to stay hydrated, eat lunch, and rest. Advised father to reach out to pediatrician if any further events or questions about today event

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My mom, got her first Moderna shot on Feb. 4th, 2021 and developed trombosis in the legs about a week later.  She went to the doctor, who at first didn't want to see her and told her to elevate her leg. Pt. had a scheduled eye appointment on Feb. 12th  with an other doctor and when she asked if she had any other issues, pt. showed her her leg.  The eye doctor immediately told her to go to urgent care.  When she did she received blood thinners and started injections in her stomach for 5 days.  Feb. 18th pt. suffered a mini stroke and went to the hospital emergency room.  She was transferred over to another facility in the afternoon and kept overnight.  She had a phone appointment with the Dr. on Feb. 24th and on the 26th she received a heart monitor to wear for 2 weeks.  She also had a check up about her leg, which was still swollen.   On March 4, pt. received her second Moderna shot and she was feverish and very tired for days and weeks after.  By March 18th her condition didn't improve at all and in fact she was felling really bad over night, so on March 19th she was admitted again to the hospital.  She was  monitored and kept over night, but  during the early morning she suffered a stroke and a heart attack and passed way the next day.
OTHER_MEDS: high cholesterol medication, low dose aspirin and some vitamins
CUR_ILL: double vision and some dizziness a few months prior

Patient received the 1st COVID vaccine (Pfizer lot # EW0182 use by 5/15/2021) at 1455. The client had a history of fainting (x3) with intramuscular injections. The client reported eating lunch prior to arriving for her appointment. The client was vaccinated in the anti-gravity chair at 1455 by EMT. The client became very pale about 1 minute following the vaccination administration and she loss consciousness for 5 seconds, during this time she had 2 myoclonic contractions. RN and EMT immediately placed the patient in Fowler's position in the anti-gravity chair during the syncopal episode. The patient immediately regained consciousness and was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The patient remained in Fowler's position and vitals were taken at 1456: BP 125/95 (R arm), HR 45, RR 18, and oxygen saturation at 95%. The patient denied experiencing lightheadedness, shortness of breath, dizziness, nausea, headache, or blurry vision. The patient was given a juice box. The patient's color slowly returned. Vitals were retaken at 1505: BP 123/82 (R arm), RR 20, HR 50, oxygen saturation at 98%. The patient stated, " I usually feel really bad after I faint but this time I feel fine." Vitals at 1510 were as follows: BP 130/70, RR 18, HR 67, oxygen saturation at 100%. The patient was speaking in full sentences and laughing with her friend. Vitals taken at 1515: BP 125/ 68, RR 16, HR 68, oxygen saturation at 99%. The patient was positioned from a Fowler's position to sitting upright. The patient's color returned to her face and she denied any nausea, dizziness, blurred vision, double vision, or chest pain. Vitals were taken at 1520: BP 125/70, HR 82, RR 16, oxygen saturation at 99%. At 1524, the patient's blood pressure was 125/68 and HR was 58. The patient continued to deny any shortness of breath, dizziness, nausea, or vision changes. The patient's heart rate was taken at 1531, HR 55 and again at 1536, HR 62. The patient's mother stated her daughter was currently taking an antibiotic for acne (dosage and name unknown) and denied having any drug allergies or  chronic medical conditions. RN instructed the patient and her mother about emergency precautions and to follow up with their primary care provider. RN, also educated the patient and her mother about the importance of informing the healthcare provider about her history of fainting with injections when receiving the second COVID Pfizer vaccine.  Gave the patient's mother V-safe information and reported the occurrence in VAERS. The patient had a steady and even gait when leaving the site with her mother at 1537.
OTHER_MEDS: Antibiotic for acne, drug name and dosage unknown
PRIOR_VAX: Hx of fainting with injections, unknown if it was with a vaccine injection

Four weeks after send dose of Pfizer experience Stroke-like symptoms such as numbness  on left face, arm and leg; confusing head; sharpness of skin sense declined. Hospital ED, did multiple tests including MRI.
LAB_DATA: IMPRESSION:   1. No evidence of acute or subacute infarct. No evidence of intracranial mass.  2. Fairly extensive nonspecific white matter changes for the patient's age. Differential considerations include hypertension, diabetes, migraine headaches, and vasculitis. The distribution of lesions would be markedly atypical for demyelinating disease such as multiple sclerosis. Narrative MRI BRAIN WITHOUT CONTRAST  HISTORY: Left-sided paresthesias. Dizziness. Clinical stroke. (5/13/2021)  FINDINGS: No acute or subacute infarct on the diffusion-weighted images. No evidence of intracranial hemorrhage. Fairly extensive foci of increased T2 signal intensity are seen in the deep central and subcortical white matter of bilateral cerebral hemispheres, nonspecific. No intra-axial or extra-axial masses are visualized. Cortical sulci, lateral ventricles, and basilar cisterns are normal in size and configuration. Normal flow voids in the blood vessels at the base of the brain.   Orbits appear normal. Mastoid air cells demonstrate normal signal intensity. Paranasal sinuses demonstrate normal signal intensity. Clival and calvarial marrow signal intensity is normal.

I received my second Moderna shot on 4/9/2021. I was sick for about 36 hours and it went away. No big deal. On 4/12 I got my period. I haven?t had a period in 3 years because of my birth control. I had really bad cramping and lots of clots. It lasted about 5 days and was gone. On 4/30 I got another period. Same lots of clotting and bad cramps. That went away after about 5-6 days.  I went to the dr on 4/13 and told her about it which she ignored and said it could be anything. She will run labs but won?t check estrogen levels since I?m on birth control. I go for labs on Monday 4/17.  Well on 4/15, which is the day I am writing this I am again on my period. This isn?t normal. As well as the pains that I am constantly feeling in what feels like my tubes or something. I also know I am not the only person this has happened to. The shots have just became available for teens and I have a 14, 12 and 6 year. All girls. And I am all for the shot however this makes me question if it won?t affect my daughters and how it will affect them if it?s doing this to me.  I am hesitant to give it to them and I wasn?t before.
LAB_DATA: Labs scheduled for 4/17 but I doubt will tell me anything since estrogen isn?t being checked.  Going to also ask about an ultrasound to check everything when I go for labs on Monday.
OTHER_MEDS: Birth control, Zoloft and allergy medicine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient stated that she had not received a vaccine in several years but that the last time she did, she blacked out for maybe 30 seconds and felt dizzy. She states she thinks it was because she did not eat that day and stood up too quickly because she felt ok after. I notified (pharmacist) to be on stand by in case any incidence occurred and we had smelling salts and epipen on hand. I had the patient sit in the vaccine chair afterwards and about 3 minutes later, she started screaming to the top of her lungs that she felt like she was going to die. She screamed that she couldn't breathe and that her chest and head were "killing her". She kept screaming to remove the vaccine out of her arm (the liquid). Her eyes were starting to roll, but I knew she was breathing because she was screaming to not let her die. Her mother was with her and was very nervous and wanted emergency services, so We called 911. I took the girls hands and asked her to look me in the eyes and follow my deep breaths, because I began to think it was more of a panic attack. She followed by breaths and regained some composure but was sweating profusely, so I began fanning her. After a while of talking her through taking deep breaths and assuring her she was breathing and we had emergency services on the way, she began to calm down. EMS showed up about 15-20 minutes later and she declined to go with them. I stayed with the patient the entire time. She did not faint. I believe she just had a panic attack from working herself up about the vaccine. She was a little scared since she had fainted with the last vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient vaccinated at 10:18am by mobile vaccinator. At 10:48am patient reported symptoms of headache rated 4/10, chest heaviness that lasted a ?few? moments, and lightheadedness. Patient?s 30 minute wait increased to 45 minutes by mobile team. Patient given Gatorade and instructed to recline seat, patient declined any breathing issues. Patient?s new wait time now 11:03am from 10:48am. When checking on patient at 11:05am, patient informed her headache has increased and moved to sinuses and reported chest heaviness had returned. Patient?s spouse reported that patient used her inhaler before the RN came to car. MBC paged at 11:08am to come for further evaluation. Patient?s vital signs taken at 11:15am were a pulse of 84, blood pressure of 138/82, and pulse oximetry of 97%. Patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and event. And able to hold a conversation. MBC called EMS at 11:17am, and continued to monitor patient for any status changes. No hives, itchiness, tongue swelling, or respiratory obstruction were noted. EMS arrived at 11:29am and performed an evaluation. Vital signs were a pulse of 89, blood pressure of 145/89, and pulse oximetry of 96% at room air. At 11:35am, patient reported muscle pain in her chest that radiated up to her shoulders, and no acute distress or respiratory issues. Patient declined EMS transport and left the site at 11:44am. Provided education to patient and told to follow up with primary care doctor, and if symptoms worsen to head to the nearest ER or Call EMS. Patient and spouse verbalized understanding of the education. Patient left in the passenger side of the car, spouse was driving the vehicle.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Issue: I have been dealing with nerve pain in my left arm from a terribly placed tetanus shot (Td) by immunizations since 22 Feb 21. I felt pain immediately after the shot. On a 1-10 scale, this pain stays at a 7 every hour of every day, with a break only occurring at night due to the CNS depressants (Flexeril) and Lidocaine patches. I have pins and needles type tingling flowing from the injection site all the way down to all fingers on the left arm. The second I wake back up; the pain cycle repeats. I have lost most of my range of motion in that arm (at least 50%). Believe this condition to be SIRVA (Shoulder Injury Related to Vaccine Administration).  Record of ?care?: 22 February 2021: The nurse who administered the immunization did not project or estimate where she would place the shot or bunch up the muscle with her hand, she simply jabbed it near my shoulder bone (way too high on the arm) which led me to believe the needle punctured the bursa sac & hit a nerve. The moment she did this, I immediately felt the pain I described above. The haphazard technique in which the injection was performed was incredibly negligent. 8 March: The soonest appointment I could get. PCM believed the issue to be muscle pain and believed it would resolve in 2-4 weeks. I was prescribed Flexeril and Celebrex. None of which has helped with pain, the Flexeril just puts me to sleep. I am unable to lift more than 5lbs with that arm and do simple things like put on deodorant/T-shirts, etc. without extraordinary pain (as in a more than a 7).  The PCM recommended a nerve test if there was no improvement in 2 weeks.  I believe this is definitely needed, in addition to a review of other medications that can help me with my pain during the day.  22 March: I called with appointment line as my pain is unbearable during the day. I was told the earliest date they had for an in-person would be 1 April. I wrote the PCM via my insurance asking if a nerve study could be done at that time and was told that I need to speak with my provider about that...Is that not what my insurance is meant to do? Due to the pain, I went to the ER and was prescribed an oral steroid and lidocaine patches and told it will take 2-4 months to heal. The 7-day steroids have done nothing for me, but the lidocaine patches are very helpful for pain and help me get me to sleep at night. Unfortunately, I can only use them every 12 hours, so I save them for nighttime.  1 April: PCM at suggested a steroid injection at the end April to help with physical therapy, which she just put in a referral for today (1 April). I asked if she could give it to me now if it helps but she wants to wait to see what the nerve study comes back and says, a referral for the nerve study was put in on 1 April, even though I requested it 22 March. 12/26/1992d I asked the PCM when I could expect the study and she has no idea when the nerve study will take place, but guestimates the end of April as that is when she wants to do the steroid shot. After speaking with neurology, there is no referral in for my test and referral management did not answer their phone when I tried to contact them. I visited info desk, they gave me four numbers for patient advocacy, referral mgmt. and neurology. One is an incorrect number and three of them are operable and, but no one picks up and the system states, "The mailbox you have reached cannot accept messages". The shirt gave me a number as well, but it provides the same mailbox message. I finally located the number/email for the patient advocacy on 1 April and informed them I am having an issue with care. As of 7 April, no one has called back.  6 April: Referral for a nerve consult (not test) was put in on 1 April, however no one acted on it. So, I physically went to referral management to see where it was sitting. Neurology had it, but the referral office did not have a number for them, only the consult and appointment line. After locating that office, myself, I was told a consult appointment would happen 30 April at the soonest. I stated that it was unacceptable to wait that long, given my track record of pain and I asked for the number to patient advocacy but was told they do not have it. I called referral management to get an external clinic to provide the test but received the following: ?The mailbox you have reached cannot accept messages.? I then tried the help desk, who gave me the number for the Facility. I was not able to catch the name, but I gave her the summary of my issues. I was returned a call by staff at referral management who said he will work with Agency to get my referral off-base since 30 April is far too long given my level of pain. There is a ?30-day access of care? standard but since I have been trying to receive this care since 22 March that 30 days is exceeded.  7 April: Went back to the ER due to the pain and was prescribed Cymbalta, which I only took for two weeks and then weaned off due to heavy depression.  12 April: EMG test at facility was performed. Test was excruciating, Dr. told me some people go to sleep because they have to lay there for so long (45min) Findings were abnormal but still listed as ?normal?. No comparison test was performed on my right arm to confirm a difference. Also, the test was performed the entire time with a ring on my finger (left arm) which I found out later was not great for accurate results. I was told to look forward to finding something with my MRI.  3 May: Went to with the Physical Therapist to get started as the PCM requested. The Dr. asked me to perform several exercises with a lacrosse ball. Then asked to put my arm above my head, which I could not do. He asked to force it up with my right arm and even though I tried it was not going to happen due to the incredible pain. Follow up visit scheduled 18 May. 7 May: Went to facility for an MRI ? process took 20min and was told the results would be avail in the next 3 business days.  15 May: Still waiting for an MRI review/phone call.
LAB_DATA: X-ray - 08 Mar 21 Nerve Conduction Test - 12 Apr 21 MRI - 07 May 21 Physical Therapy - Began 03 May 21

I got vaccinated last Friday afternoon, was sore Saturday morning, and got intense chills Saturday afternoon and went to bed (wore two layers of clothing and had three blankets plus my heater going).  On Sunday the 9th, early morning (4:20am), I went to the restroom and passed out/fell after washing my hands.  It happened again trying to get to my room, and a third time trying to turn on my light when my roommate called out wondering what all the noise was.  My speech was slurred, my vision black and fuzzy, and I could barely hear her voice.  I also was sweating a lot.  It took about five minutes for me to become coherent enough to call the 24 hour nurse line.  Though I was coherent, I couldn't stand without feeling dizzy, and was advised to call 911.  Paramedics ran tests to see if my blood sugar/anything stroke related could be the cause, and the doctor/nurses at the ER ran blood tests as well.  Everything came back normal, and they concluded my passing out was likely due to the vaccine.  I was discharged around noon, and since then have not fallen or felt the same level of dizziness.
LAB_DATA: All tests performed on 05/09/2021. Ambulance performed tests associated with stoke and low blood sugar, all came back normal. In ER, doctor and nurses performed general physical exams, echocardiogram, blood tests, urine test, all came back normal. Only some soreness where I bumped my head, and random scrapes and bruises from falling.

Patient did not want me to call an ambulance and person with him told me not to call. We waited a little longer, patient complained of feeling really hot. He laid down on the floor and I gave him some water and a lollipop to increase sugar levels. After 3-5 minutes patient sat down on the chair and stated he was feeling much better. After a few minutes, he complained of wanting to vomit. As soon as I was able to give him a bag, he violently threw up. Patient stated that he was now feeling much better. He went to the bathroom and cleaned up. After a little longer observation, patient said he was fine and wanted to go home. They left. I called patient an hour later and he stated he felt fine and was just resting. Will follow up with patient tomorrow.

I started having vaginal bleeding on April 14th. The first day, it was the same amount as a regular period. In the days following, the bleeding became very heavy, having me go through a super-sized tampon with a pad every 1 and a half to two hours along with several large blood clots each time changing. On the 15th, I called the on-call nurse for my gynocologist and she said that it might have been from the vaccine and taking birth control, since many patients of hers had called with the same problem. The bleeding continued at this rate all the way until my second dose on April 29th. I saw my primary doctor that day and she tested my hemoglobin, which came up at 10.7, which was slightly anemic. She prescribed an Iron supplement and told me to skip my "period" days and go straight to my next pack of birth control when the one I was using was finished. The next day, I experienced severe nausea, diarrhea, chills, fever-like symptoms, difficulty breathing, and extreme fatigue. I went to the Emergency Room, and they gave me about an IV and a half. They said I had extreme dehydration, and was slightly more anemic than when tested the day before.  Following that day, the bleeding was significantly lighter and then stopped for a few days on the following Thursday when I started my new pack of birth control. I had little to no blood for.a couple days, followed by bloody discharge up until Tuesday night, the 11th of May, when the bleeding started again, being about the same amount as a regular period. I am still currently bleeding at this rate.
LAB_DATA: Hemoglobin on 29th: 10.7 Hemoglobin on 30th: 10.4  Diagnosis from ER: Anemia, Menorrhagia, Possible adverse reaction to COVID-19 vaccine, Weakness
OTHER_MEDS: Yaz Probiotic  Zinc Vitamin D Quadrafolate Vitamin B

Although this is not a significant adverse reaction, it seems important that state and CDC advise families that COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine in youth can cause abnormal blood sugars including lows. We did have two days of unusual lows which required we treat with standard 15-15 method.  Given that we utilize a CGM, we were able to constantly monitor but I would have been concerned for families that do not have this technology. After noting lows, I contacted multiple peers whom also have T1D children whom have had similar experiences. I clearly believe the benefit outweighs the risk and will have my son complete the series of vaccines but do believe it is important that families are notified to monitor blood glucose levels more frequently post vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day of my first dose (January 23) I felt a bit numb in the head but thought it would be okay. That did clear up.  I was however very weak after the first dose but improved.  By February 7, I had been feeling pulsations in my head and I checked that I had a BP over 200/100 and went to the ER. I was given a low dose amplodipine however my primary care doctor checked my urine and found very high proteinuria. Eventually I followed up with a nephrologist after being given an urgent referral and was diagnosed with membrane nephropathy due to high PLA2R levels. My proteinuria was 13 g/day (severe) and I had very high cholesterol and low serum albumin (2.5 mg/dl).  He mentioned that the vaccine has unmasked it in several people.  I have received treatment of 10 mg Lisinopril, 20 mg Simvastatin, 81 mg aspirin and have received my first infusion of 1 g Rituximab and will follow with a second infusion 2 weeks later.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 34 year old Female with a past medical history of pseudo-seizures. Her past allergies are shrimp (Unknown), Tylenol/ Advil/ Alieve (Unknown).  She has 4 anti-seizure medications on her medication list: Zonisamide, Lamotrigine, Lyrica, Levetiracetam. She has had these pseudo-seizures in the past, but according to her sister who was her emergency contact, she has not had one in the past 1.5 years. The vaccinator did not she had baseline right hand weakness as well pre vaccination.  The patient was vaccinated at 1406 in her right arm.  A staff member noticed that the patient was not feeling well and went to check on the patient. She started presenting with grand-mal seizure symptoms at 1442, and she was lowered to the ground. Staff was with her and was protecting her head and trying to keep her on her side. EMS was called around 1445  and arrived around 1455. At this point the seizure symptoms continued. The patient would appear to be coming out of it and then when someone would say anything the convulsions would get stronger. At 1506 EMS administered 5mg of versed, which did not bring the patient out of the seizure. The patient was seizing for 24 min at this point and was still breathing, but the thought was in case it is not a pseudo-seizure.   At 1509 the patient?s sister arrived and had explained that this happens in the past and she is able to be talked out of her seizure.  Her sister describes them as ?behavioral seizures? At 1515 the patient came too and was alert and oriented.  Around 1525 the patient was taken to Hospital with EMS. EMS staff that transported the patient. The patient and sister were agreeable to the plan as the event lasted 33 minutes. It is unclear if the vaccine caused this seizure or if it was provoked by anxiety and stimulation. It was recommended to consult their provider on receiving a second dose.
CUR_ILL: Pt stated her R hand was weak from the past, but did not tell the administering nurse why. This was not new

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On May 9th I began to experience severe pain in my back extending down my left side. The pain was severe enough to prevent sleeping that night. The pain continued throughout May 10th becoming worse with deep breaths or any type of internal strain (cough, sneeze, etc). That evening, I took two Tylenol and later two Ibuprofen and was able to sleep. The pain persisted for the next week, slowly improving but not fully going away. On May 15th I conducted a telemedicine appointment and was advised to go to either Urgent Care or the ER. I chose the ER at  Hospital. A D-Dimer test showed elevated results and a CT scan was ordered. The CT revealed blood clots in my right lung, specifically "Subpleural conslidation in the posterior basilar segment the right lower lobe is present, compatible with pulmonary infarct. Question additional pulmonary infarct in the lateral basilar segment the lower right lobe. Probable atelectasis in the left lung base." MD prescribed Eliquis @ 10mg 2x daily and I was discharged with a referral to    .
LAB_DATA: D-Dimer, CT scan "Helical axial images were performed after the administration of IV contrast with multiple reconstructions. Coronal MIP images through the chest were also generated. CT dose-reducing technique was utilized." Contrast was "75 mL Isovue 370"

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is an 80 y/o right handed female who is totally independent at baseline who received her Pfizer vaccine out of the country (1st dose 2/19/21, 2nd dose 3/12/21).  She was reactive to both shots, reporting arthralgias, headache, low grade fever, chills. She had a rise in blood pressure later during the day of her shot as well as the next day (up to 180/70, from baseline of 130/70). She also had an episode of epistaxis several days after her first shot.  She traveled independently out of the country on 3/31/21 to visit her son on a leisure trip. On 4/5/21 she had headache, dizziness/lightheadedness, and did not feel well, and her systolic BP was 198, after which she took additional 40 mg of lisinopril.   Her BP subsequently decreased to systolic BP of 130 mm Hg on 4/5/21, but over the next few days she had labile BP with a range of BP of 125 to 171/ 58 - 68.  She was meticulous in checking and recording her BP several times a day, and she increased her lisinopril dose to 40 mg po qd from 20 mg po qd given the higher than usual blood pressure range.  On 4/10/21 her BP was as follows: 6:30 am, 148/60 (she took her daily lisinopril 20 mg po); 11:30 am:  132/52; 3 pm: 171/69 (she took additional lisinopril 20 mg po) after which her systolic BP decreased to 130. Then around 6:20 pm the same day (4/10/21), she had acute onset of headache, vomiting, left sided weakness, SBP 220, and was witnessed to have rapid change in mental status. There was no antecedent trauma to the head. EMTs were called immediately and she had loss of consciousness during the ambulance ride to the ED, after about 20 minutes of symptom onset, with agonal breathing and bradycardia to the 40s, but never lost her pulse. Upon arrival to the ED out of the country, her Glascow Coma Scale (GCS) was 6, she was rapidly intubated and stabilized. Head CT demonstrated massive intraparenchymal hemorrhage (140 cc) within the R temporal parietal and occipital lobes, with cerebral edema and 14 mm midline shift, associated with small subdural hematoma and small intraventricular hemorrhage within the temporal horn and body of the R lateral ventricle. They reported hyperdense "spot sign" within the intraparenchymal hematoma compatible with active hemorrhage, no evidence of venous thrombosis, no masses, no arteriovenous malformations. She had 2.5 mm aneurysm right  that was thought to be incidental finding unrelated to her event. She was taken emergently to the OR on 4/10/2021 for decompressive R hemicraniectomy, which she underwent successfully with minimal blood loss.  She had no coagulopathy and her platelets and hemoglobin were normal. She remained in the Neuro ICU for 3 weeks. She received a tracheostomy two weeks after her presentation, and was weaned off the ventilator. She is breathing spontaneously after 5 weeks from presentation. She remains in coma or minimally conscious state, with GCS score of 5-6 as of 5/13/2021.
LAB_DATA: 4/10/2021: Head CT: massive intraparenchymal hemorrhage (140 cc) within the R temporal parietal and occipital lobes, with cerebral edema and 14 mm midline shift, associated with small subdural hematoma and small intraventricular hemorrhage within the temporal horn and body of the R lateral ventricle.   4/10/2021 Head and neck CTA had hyperdense "spot sign" within the intraparenchymal hematoma compatible with active hemorrhage, and 2.5 mm aneurysm right, no evidence of CVST. No significant stenoses, no significant atheroslcerosis, no evidence of venous thrombosis, no masses, no arteriovenous malformations. She had 2.5 mm aneurysm right  that was thought to be incidental finding unrelated to her event.   4/11/2021 Head CT: s/p right decompression craniectomy and evacuation of large right sided cerebral hemispheric intracranial hematoma with less mass effect on the midline structures (5-6 mm midline shift). Mild periventricular white matter changes of microangiopathy. There is no significant cerebral or cerebellar atrophy.  4/16/2021 Brain MRI/MRV: Scattered subacute ischemic infarcts in the R thalamus, subjacent basal ganglia mesial temporal lobe, right sided periatrial location and watershed distribution. Additional infarct in R pons. Mild edematous changes in brainstem possibly related to previous side to side compression. Major arteries and dural venous sinuses show gross patency based on flow related signal loss. Mild compression on R lateral ventricle with 6 mm leftward persistent midline shift. Brain parechyma: Evolving extensive R temporoparietal occipital parenchymal hemorrhage with associated edema and mass effect. A few small focal hemorrhages R subthalamus. S/p right craniectomy with approximately 5 additional epidural hemorrhage at the craniectomy site. No new parenchymal hemorrhage. MRV: Transverse sinuses, superior sagittal sinuses, and superficial veins appear patent. Patent straight sinus. Patent vein of Galen and internal cerebral veins.   Of note, the neuroimaging reported above was also reviewed directly in consultation by Neuroradiology at the Women's Hospital at her home town who confirmed the above findings. Notably, the MRI/A did not satisfy criteria for cerebral amyloid angiopathy, nor was it typical for hypertension-related intracerebral hemorrhage (which tends to be deep in the brain and focal). In summary, the neuroimaging findings were not typical for any of the potential etiologies on the differential diagnosis for lobar hemorrhage, including amyloid angiopathy, hypertensive-related hemorrhage, AVM, masses, venous thrombosis, atherosclerosis/ischemic vascular disease, or vasculitis.  Laboratory results: 4/10/2021: Hemoglobin 11.6 mg/dL, Na 127, Cl 94, aPTT 24.5, PT 11.0, INR 1.0, Platelets 224, glucose 8.6 mmol/L, CRP 8 mg/dL.  4-11/2021: WBC 16.5, hemoglobin 9.6 mg/dL, Platelets 248, Na 133, K 3,8, CL 100, Creatinine 71 umol/L, GFR >60. 4/10/2021: Chest X ray: no acute or concerning cardiopulmonary abnormalities. 4/10/2021: EKG: normal sinus rhythm, no acute changes.  4/12/2021: ECHO: Normal LV size and systolic function, EF 64%. Mild concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. Normal RV size and function. Mild pulmonary hypertension. Biatrial dilation. Aortic valve sclerosis without significant stenosis, mild aortic regurgitation.  4/14/2021: von Willebrand factor antigen and activity were not decreased.   Heparin induced thrombocytopenia test ELISA negative.

After fever broke I continue to have headaches through filling out this form along with sharp pains in my lower left leg on the front of the leg. I also have a lot of pain in the upper right glute as if I had been hit my something quite hard. For about 48 hours while these symptoms occurred I remained in bed and tried to drink water. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 19 year old patient came to pharmacy with dad to get first dose of Moderna Vaccine. Questionnaire was completed online with no's to all questions. Patient was sitting in booth and seemed comfortable while getting vaccine, but immediately after started to lean towards wall and faint. Patient's father and I supported patient so he didn't fall and injure himself. Patient was nonresponsive for about 5 to 10 seconds before he became responsive. He was able to sit by himself after about 1 minute of support from his dad. Patient was given water and waited 15 minutes in the booth while being monitored. He seemed to be himself after about 5 minutes. During those 15 minutes I talked to patient's dad about patient's medical history. He may had 1 seizure when he was younger due to ADHD medication but test results did not confirm it as a seizure. He also passed out one time in high school while watching biology movies with blood. Discussing this incident with the father and patient, we agreed this patient seems to have suffered from syncope due to fear of needles. I gave his father my business card and told him to call me if the patient reported any symptoms after leaving or if he had any questions whatsoever. I let them know I would be reporting this to VAERS and encouraged him to follow up with his PCP about this incident.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The 1st episode was April 22nd (got 1st COVID vaccine dose April 16th - 6 days prior), the 2nd was May 13th (got 2nd COVID vaccine dose May 7th - 6 days prior). Both started in the evening around 8:30pm, around an hour after I?d finished eating. It started with a feeling of burning in the back of my throat that I thought was heartburn, so I took Tums. That didn?t seem to help, and it progressed to a feeling of burning at the back of my throat and down my esophagus as well as feeling like I had gas stuck stuck between my throat and stomach and needed to burp repeatedly. It was really uncomfortable to lie down ? that seemed to increase the discomfort and burning sensations, so I ended up basically walking laps for an hour plus and burping continuously till the pressure lessened enough that I finally felt like I could lie down. The second time in happened, I also ended up throwing up, which didn?t really seem to make me feel much better. About 30 min into each episode, I also developed a pretty intense headache around my temples, as well as a stuffy nose and eventually what felt like a sinus headache as well. After about 2 hours I was able to fall asleep and mostly slept through the night. I woke up feeling better, but still having some lingering symptoms - primarily the headache and a bit of a burning sensation in the back of my throat.

Patient was given Pfizer Vaccine on 5/16/21 at 11:00-11:10am.  I read through the patient medical history through the handheld and noticed there was "yes" on seizure history.  I ask the mother what happened and she told me it was from the first incident with the Pfizer vaccine.  At the time of the first incident the mother stated that patient fainted and convulsed upon regaining consciousness.  Patient has had no history of seizures prior to then or had any big injuries that could trigger it.  Patient's mother states physicians think it's triggered by anxiety and not a true seizure, so MRI or tests was not needed.  Doctor recommended patient to come back if it happens again.  With the information provided I used professional judgement and was on high alert with the patient.               After administrating the vaccine to the patient, I monitored patient's vitals carefully. Patient was stable and I walked with him to his seat near the wall and left him with his family.  About a few minutes later the mother told me to come to her aid.  Patient had a 1 time continuous seizure for about 30 seconds-1minute.  After regaining consciousness the patient said he did not remember getting the vaccine. Patient's mother was very concerned and under control and did not overreact to the situation.  Also, I promptly relayed to (pharmacist) to call 911 and he called a member of management.  While pharmacist was on the phone with 911 the patient regained consciousness.  I monitored patient's vitals while I waited for a member of store management.  Store management took a little bit longer to respond (5-10 minutes) but arrived to document the whole incident.               About 30 minutes after the incident patient's vitals were stable and the ambulance was not needed and the family took him to the hospital to get monitored. Patient rode the electric wheelchair was escorted out by store management to the car.
PRIOR_VAX: 04/24/2021 Pfizer Covid vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient (DOB 05-01-2003) received his 1st COVID vaccine (Pfizer, lot # EW0182 use by 5/15/21 at 0855) at 1539. The patient became pale approximately 30 seconds following the administration of the vaccine, EMT assisted the patient to the chair as he was standing up when he became pale, the patient loss consciousness for approximately 2 seconds. RN arrived at the station and assisted the patient to the ground, where he was placed in a supine position with his lower extremities elevated. The patients face mask was removed, he was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The patients color slowly returned to his face. Vitals were taken at 1540: BP: 155/70 (R arm, supine position), HR 70, RR 16, oxygen saturation at 97%, and pupils were equal. The patient had a history of fainting x 1 and his last meal was at 0800 and he stated, " I didn't drink that much today." Denied any chronic medical conditions, was not currently taking any medications, and denied any drug allergies. The patient was moved to the anti-gravity chair and he was given pringles and Gatorade. Vitals were retaken at 1545: BP 162/80 (R arm, sitting upright), HR 50, RR 16, oxygen saturation at 97%. Denied any dizziness, headache, chest pain, or vision changes.  Vitals were retaken at 1553: BP 158/72 (R arm, sitting upright), HR 52, RR 16, Oxygen saturation at 97%. The patient was advised to eat a full meal prior to receiving his second COVID vaccine dose and to receive his 2nd dose in the anti-gravity chair. Vitals were retaken at 1558, BP 152/78 (R arm, sitting upright), HR 57, RR 16, and oxygen saturation at 98%. The patient was also given a bottle of water, as he did not consume many liquids during the day. The patient's color fully returned to his face and he denied any shortness of breath, dizziness, changes in vision, or difficulty swallowing. Vitals retaken at 1603, BP 150/75 ( R arm, sitting upright), HR 60, RR 16, and oxygen saturation at 96%. The patient called his mother to pick him up, as we strongly advised him to not operate machinery/ a vehicle after fainting. The patient's vital signs were taken at 1608, BP 140/75, HR 60, RR 16, and oxygen saturation at 100%. The patient was advised to drink the entire bottle of water, as his blood pressure was slightly elevated and it was most likely due to being dehydrated, as he did not consume any fluid since 0800 earlier that day. The patient drank a bottle of water and his vital signs were retaken at 1614, BP 122/68 (R arm, sitting upright) and a respiratory rate of 15 breaths per minute. The patient's mother arrived on site around 1630 and spoke with RN and both EMT. RN instructed the patient about emergency precautions and to follow up with his primary care provider. RN also educated the patient about the importance of informing the healthcare provider about his history of fainting with the first vaccine, when receiving the second COVID Pfizer vaccine. Gave the patient V-safe information and reported the occurrence in VAERS. The patient had a steady and even gait when leaving the site with his mother at 1632.

Patient received the 2nd COVID vaccine (Pfizer, lot #EW0182, use by date 05/17/21 at 1515) at 1438. The patient reported feeling dizzy to EMT, who immediately moved him to the anti-gravity chair. RN assisted in positioning him in a Fowler's position and ice packs were placed on his back and behind his neck. Patient's face mask was removed and his vital signs were taken at 1459, the patient was wearing a thick jacket, so the palpable radial pulse on the left forearm was 145, HR 83, RR 16, oxygen saturation was 97%., and pupils were equal. The patient denied any shortness of breath, difficulty breathing, difficulty swallowing, chest pain, or loss of consciousness. The patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The patient was speaking in full sentences and immediately responsive to questions. The patient was given a bottle of water and reported last eating around 1300. The patients color slowly reappeared when he was placed in Fowler's position. Reported being allergic to penicillin and taking Seroquil, 400mg, daily and Hydroxyzine, 25 mg for anxiety. Denied any chronic medical disorders other than general anxiety. Vitals were retaken at 1459, BP: palpable radial pulse, 140, RR 16, HR 79, and oxygen saturation at 98%. The patient stated that he felt flushed in his face, and the patient was immediately offered Benadryl but he stated, " Let's wait a few minutes, I don't like taking anything if I don't have to."The patient denied any shortness of breath, difficulty breathing or swallowing, lip tingling, or facial swelling. The patient decided to take the oral Benadryl at 1503 and was given Benadryl, 50mg oral suspension, PO. At 1505 we attempted to position him to a sitting upright position in the gravity chair and he stated, " I feel lightheaded, can we place me back how I was?" EMT and RN repositioned the patient in the anti-gravity chair to a Fowler's position and assisted the patient with removing two layers of shirts, as he was wearing multiple layers. Vitals were retaken at 1506: 120 palpable radial pulse, RR 16, HR 78, and oxygen saturation at 97%. The patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The patient was able to follow commands, had strength equal bilaterally in the upper extremities, and had a symmetrical smile. Vitals were retaken at 1515, BP: 120/82 (R arm), HR 81, RR 16, oxygen saturation at 97%. The patient was given juice and repositioned to a semi-Fowler's position. Denied dizziness or lightheadedness. The patient stated, " I'm usually pretty sensitive to medication, now I just feel like I could go to sleep." Denied experiencing shortness of breathing, difficulty swallowing, or difficulty breathing. Vitals were retaken at 1528, BP 120/85, HR 66, RR 16, oxygen saturation at 98%.  The patient was able to follow commands, and stated, " I feel a pressure in my head." RN was going to call 911 to have EMS transport the patient to a hospital, but the patient denied EMS services and did not want 911 to be called when it  was offered at 1528. The patient was repositioned to a Fowler's position. Patient reported no longer feeling flushed on the left side of his face at 1535. At 1540, vitals were retaken, BP 120/85 ( R arm, sitting upright), HR 79, RR 16, and oxygen saturation at 97%. The patient's color returned and he denied feeling lightheaded or dizzy. RN instructed the patient about emergency precautions and to follow up with his primary care provider.  RN educated the patient about not operating machinery as the patient was given Benadryl and this may cause him to be drowsy. The patient contacted a friend to pick him up from the site. RN  gave the patient reporting information. Vitals were retaken at 1550, BP: 120/82, HR 76, RR 16, and oxygen saturation at 98%. The patient's mouth was moving with regular movements and the patient was rapidly responding to questions. Patient called friend to coordinate his ride home. RN educated him about ER precautions again. The patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation, and his facial color had returned to baseline. EMT was instructed to stay with the patient until patient's friend arrived on site. At 1610  EMT reported to  RN that patient reported feeling flushed and lightheaded again. EMT immediately placed him in a Fowler's position and RN called 911, EMS. The patient stated, " It's hard for me to recall things, like my head is really foggy." Patient's speech was slower than baseline, no facial swelling was observed and patient denied any difficulty breathing, shortness of breath, chest pain, or loss of consciousness. Patient was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. Fire Department  assumed care at 1615, RN gave report to the responders. The responders completed an EKG on site and completed a set of vitals. Patient denied transportation by EMS to hospitaland signed AMA paperwork given to him by the responders. Patient's friend arrived on site at 1618. RN educated patient's friend about transporting patient to hospital, as patient stated, " I'm going to have my friend take me to the hospital." RN quickly educated patient's friend  that if while transporting patient to hospital, he began to experience shortness of breath, loss of consciousness, or difficulty breathing, to immediately pull over and call 911. Patient's friend verbalized understanding and patient was pushed in a wheelchair to the friend's vehicle, as he was very lightheaded. EMT,  EMT, and RN assisted patient into the vehicle. Patient and friend stated that they were going to pick up a few items from patient's car and then go to the hospital immediately. Patient left the site at 1621.

Rash developed morning of 4/26/21, saw PCP that afternoon who prescribed antihistamine hydroxyzine to take instead of Benadryl. Later that evening, sudden onset of tachycardia and extreme dizziness, so I went to the ER. ER doctor gave me 60mg prednisone followed by another three days at 40mg, and sent me home an hour later after it was clear the rash was responding to the prednisone. Beginning in the afternoon of 4/28/21, I suddenly felt like my body weighed a million pounds and like I had been drugged, like I was excessively relaxed and moving in slow motion, but my HR was high. I saw Dr. the following day, 4/29, when I was still feeling heavy, slow, and sedated. She was concerned about my HR and did an ECG which was normal. Later that night, I woke up in the middle of the night with the opposite sensation, like my body was in a full on fight or flight response for no apparent reason, my heart racing and my blood pumping so forcefully through my veins it was slightly painful. I got up and took my BP and it was 145/75. The next evening I developed chest pain in addition to continued tachycardia so I went back to the ER. The ECG they did was also normal but they did no further testing. The doctor explained what I was experiencing must be a side effect of the prednisone and should go away now that I was off of it. This whole time in addition to tachycardia I had been feeling generally ill, weak, shaky, developed a tremor, nauseous, lost a few pounds. I continued to experience tachycardia and unusual blood pressure fluctuations in the second weak following the vaccination but the nausea, weakness, and tremor subsided. In particular, I have developed orthostatic intolerance, with my HR jumping to 120s upon standing and into the 130s-140s when on my feet for more than a few minutes at a time. During this time I have been unable to work normally and unable to care for my two-year-old daughter. I noticed some improvement in my HR issues beginning 5/5/21 but since then I have still been having good and bad days. I had another episode when I went to see an allergist regarding my vaccine reaction on 5/11/21, and they took my vitals reclined (BP 95/59, HR 110), seated (BP 100/62, HR 126), and standing (BP 102/74, HR 136). The allergist said my reaction to the vaccine was a morbilliform rash and was not an allergic reaction, but likely an overactive immune response due to having had Covid in March 2020.
LAB_DATA: ECG 5/6/21; CBC, TSH, metabolic panel 5/6/21; ECG 5/7/21

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 15 hours of receiving the injection, I was unable to move my left arm from my left side and was in excruciating pain. I experienced complete immobility of this arm for 4 days and was unable to do basic activities (i.e. putting a shirt on and off, opening cupboards, driving, etc). My sleep was very poor due to the pain and fear of what this would mean for my life. I went back to the doctor's office where I had received the vaccination for guidance as to what to do next and she gave me an RX to help with sleep, suggested I use Menthol rub for the pain, use anti-inflammatory medication and gave me some static exercises to help support recovery.  She said this type of condition can take 6-9 months to heal. Since I wasn't finding much relief from the extreme pain and my arm mobility continued to be very limited, I sought out a Physical Therapist about a couple weeks after receiving the vaccination. After his initial examination, he described my condition as "frozen shoulder" and provided exercises to strengthen the muscles in the shoulder in a way that would work around the vaccination injury and give my arm mobility.  This was very helpful and slowly I found ways to deal better with the pain and began to have better movement of the arm and overall rehabilitation from the injury.  I worked with him for 3 weeks and he gave me exercises that I could continue to do at home for ongoing recovery.  I also sought out a chiropractor during this time, but the arm was too painful for any significant work to be done on it. Finally, I went to a massage therapist who provided therapeutic massage to help ease and relax the tightness in my neck and shoulder from the chronic pain I was experiencing.  This too was helpful as I found myself holding my body so tight as a result of the immense pain.  I have now, about 9 months later, regained almost all mobility with minimal limitations still present.  I can still feel the pain in my shoulder when I touch the injection site area and there are days it aches or I will have a shooting pain with a particular movement.  It can also feel painful at times when I do exercises like push-ups, but I started working weekly with a Physical Therapist again in April 2021 to help stabilize that shoulder joint with more focused exercises.  I last met with the Physical Therapist on May 13th, when he encouraged me to continue the shoulder strengthening exercises at home going forward and to continue these, as the shoulder would likely need this for ongoing stabilization.  This again is proving to be helpful.

17-year old M with history of recurrent ear infections requiring PE tube placement who was in his usual state of health until 5/5 when he noticed a new itchy hive-like rash. He was short of breath 5/6, and developed fevers that night along with vomiting. He was seen 5/6 with negative COVID19 PCR and documented fever to 104. Fevers continued, and he was admitted the evening of 5/10 with concern for myocarditis. See below for hospital course. Additional information for Item 18: ...Screening labs were notable for mild lymphopenia, hyperbilirubinemia, hepatitis, and elevated inflammatory markers.  Given prior COVID infection, rash, and systemic inflammation, additional studies including troponin, D-dimer, BNP, and EKG were obtained.  EKG was reassuringly normal, however the D-dimer (2.48), troponin (1.27), and BNP (469) were elevated.  Other work-up included chest x-ray which was unremarkable, and right upper quadrant ultrasound with incidental cavernous hemangioma of the liver.  He was started on milrinone (5/11-5/12) after initial TTE was concerning for severely diminished LV function. Follow-up TTE 12 hours later was normal (on milrinone), and remained so after milrinone was discontinued 5/12. Follow-up TTE after discontinuation remained normal. Cardiac MRI was completed 5/14, although read remains pending. He received IVIG on 5/11, and was started on methylpred 50 mg IV BID, Anakinra 100 mg SQ BID 5/14,  and transitioned to prednisone 30 mg PO BID with clinical improvement, down-trending troponin and systemic inflammatory labs.  Subsequent CBCs have been notable for rising leukocytosis (5/16 WBC 56.3) and thrombocytosis (5/16 plts 690) and 4+ spherocytes (with no known personal or prior history of spherocytosis). He will likely be discharged 5/17.   Infectious evaluation was unrevealing including cultures and viral studies. COVID spike and nucleocapsid antibodies were sent, but remain pending. He received his second dose of the Pfizer COVID19 vaccine 4/27 in his left arm; denies any significant reactions (arm swelling, injection site redness, lymphadenopathy, myalgias, fatigue, or fever). On September 30,2020 I went to pharmacy. I received a flu shot from a pharmacist. The shot was high on my arm and hurt a lot. I mentioned that this was the first time a flu shot hurt like that. That night the injection site was sore and I felt pain in my shoulder. In the months following It got progressively worse. To the point I could not raise my arm up without doubling over in agony. I could not reach out for anything with my right arm. I decided to see an Orthopedic surgeon in December. I saw Dr. on December 18th 2020 he said I had locked shoulder due to inflammation possibly due to the Flu shot I had received considering that was the onset of my symptoms. I had a series of x-rays to rule out injury and there was no structural damage to my shoulder. He prescribed steroid shots and physical therapy. On December 21, 2020 I received 2 steroid shots in my shoulder. On December 23, 2020 I began physical therapy twice a week until March 9, 2021. Although the physical therapy improved my range of motion I still had pain and still have pain. I still cannot reach behind my back or into the backseat of the car or to turn off the alarm. The pain wakes me up so I don?t sleep a full night?s sleep.
LAB_DATA: Xrays and Steroid Shots and physical therapy

I was diagnosed by my neurologist with Guillain-Barre Syndrome.  9 days after my 2nd Pfizer shot (Sunday, March 28th), I felt tingling in my feet. On Monday night I felt tingling and pain in my feet, but I was sure it was passing and said nothing since the pain was manageable at a level 2?3. On Tuesday I was getting concerned. My feet were now tingling and in pain all day, and the pain had escalated to a level 5. On Wednesday I suddenly realized that my life could effectively be over soon. The pain was at a 7-8, and I could barely get through my day. My body felt like there were tiny needles shooting electricity into me, and it felt all-consuming. It was unrelenting, and I suddenly understood why the CEO (a COVID survivor) killed himself after suffering through constant ringing in his ears. It became CRYSTAL clear how chronic pain made regular working life impossible, and I wondered how I would get by on disability and how long it would take to kick in after applying. I started panicking while focusing enough to book a doctor?s appointment for that Friday. By the end of Wednesday my calves and thighs were severely cramped, and by Thursday my eyes were tingling and my hands and arms were tingling with pain. I feared MS since it runs in my family. I was terrified and confused and made an appointment with a PCP for Friday, April 2nd.
LAB_DATA: 5/7/21: Diagnosed with Acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy after 35 minutes of face to face exercises and tests by neurologist. His doctor?s notes in the  app are extensive, but I cannot copy and paste that section.

I had pain in my left shoulder immediately following my injection. I told myself that I must be getting weak as I hadn't felt like that with any previous vaccinations I have received. By the time I went to bed I couldn't raise my arm above my head. I suffered through the night unable to sleep with a pain level of about 6. The next morning the pain reduced to about a 4 as I moved the arm more throughout the day. This same cycle repeated itself over and over for the next week and a half each night the pain grew worse until it was a 9 out of 10 and was so bad it would take my breath away. The next morning I went to urgent care. After urgent care I had 4 months of physical therapy with no relief. I then had a cortisone  Shot into my left shoulder which gave me relief for only a few weeks then the pain returned. My doctor then recommended surgery to fix the problem. I had a arthroscopic procedure with bursectomy and shoulder decompression. I am now 5 weeks post surgery still with pain and doing physical therapy 2 times per week.   1. Dates: 10/21/2020 2. Received vaccine at 4 pm on Wednesday 4/28/21.  I started feeling typical vaccine side effects between 7-8 pm, and by 9 pm I went to bed exhausted.  My symptoms included SEVERE headache, fatigue, muscle aches, chills, hot flashes (no fever), nausea, stomach pain, and pain at the injection site.  I also experienced slightly blurry vision, hearing distortion, & decreased hearing -- all of which I attributed to the severe headache and assumed they would resolve when the headache resolved.  I treated with a dose of ibuprofen and later a dose of acetaminophen (I try to avoid NSAIDs and acetaminophen due to a history of ulcers in my past and current NAFLD).    My side effects lasted until 11 am Friday 4/30/21, however my hearing has not returned to normal.   My hearing in my left ear is muffled.  There is a fullness in my ear.  Although I can hear, the sound is VERY distorted -- it resembles a bad cell phone connection that sounds like it's going through a tin can and has a reverb quality to it.  I went to an ENT for evaluation on 5/5/21.  Physiologically my ear appears normal.  He started me on a 15 day taper of high dose prednisone.  I'm currently on day 12 without any improvement.  I had a thorough evaluation by an audiologist on 5/12/21 and there is hearing loss in the low range in my left ear.  At this point, I'm not hopeful that my hearing will return to normal.
LAB_DATA: 5/5/21 -- Physical exam by ENT. 5/12/21 -- Extensive testing by audiologist.  I do not know all of the testing that was performed.
OTHER_MEDS: Omeprazole 20 mg daily;  ASA 81 mg daily;  Potassium 99 mg daily

Has been taking ibuprofen for discomfort (400 mg every 4-6 hours for > 7 days). No shortness of breath. No abdominal pain.  No diarrhea. No hematuria or dysuria. No family history of sudden cardiac death or significant for CAD.  No known tick bite. Of note, received Pfizer dose 2 3d prior to symptoms starting.   Presented to ED earlier tonight where exam was notable for: Low-grade temp, mildly hypertensive with otherwise stable vitals, appears uncomfortable, belching, neck is supple without meningismus, bilateral tonsils 1+ with exudate, oropharynx is erythematous, uvula midline, no trismus, no swelling,  lungs clear, regular rhythm mild bradycardia, no murmurs rubs or gallops, abdomen is soft and nondistended with mild tenderness in epigastrium and right upper quadrant they did  ECG, bedside Echo, Strep PCR, zofran, maalox, pepcid, IVF, tylenol, and labs which were notable for elevated troponin -> 13.58 d/w YSC Ped ED and tx   Assessment:   Patient is a 17 y.o. male previously healthy who presents with 1 week of malaise, and 3 days of intermittent substernal chest pain (now resolved), found to have elevated troponin and ST segment elevations in I and lateral leads c/f myopericarditis. Etiology is unclear at this time, likely viral vs post-vaccine. Exam notable for exudative pharyngitis, however Strep and CMV neg. EBV serology with positive EBNA only. Labs otherwise notable for elevated CRP 180, ESR 38, some transaminitis, ferritin/D-dimer wnl. COVID RNA neg, spike Ab positive c/w recent COVID vaccination. Normal function on ECHO. CRP continues to downtrend. Troponin has started downtrending again and pt remains asymptomatic.        Plan   Plan:   #Myopericarditis - Repeat echo today  - q8 troponin, AM CBC, CRP, ferritin - Motrin 400mg prn - steroid taper per Rheumatology recs             30mg PO BID for 7 days             30mg PO qday for 7 days             15mg PO qday for 7 days             7.5mg PO qday for 7 days             2.5mg PO qday for 7 days             Off - f/u ID and rheum labs - continuous telemetry: patient at high risk of arrhythmia   #FEN/GI - Regular diet - strict I/O - Pepcid 20mg BID   #dispo - steroid taper sent for delivery to bedside - upon d/c start ASA - f/u cardiology - If echo today reassuring and troponin continuing to downtrend will plan for discharge this afternoon

Severe coronary artery calcifications.  4/30 Head CT: Likely new evolving lacunar infarct in the right external capsule.  5/1 Carotid US: Right Internal Carotid Artery- No significant stenosis or atherosclerotic plaque Left Internal Carotid Artery- Findings indicate <50% stenosis   Echo: Mild concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, the left ventricular systolic function is normal with an estimated EF in the range of 60-65% and trace mitral valve regurgitation.   5/1 Head MRI: Acute lacunar type infarction right external capsule with a couple of tiny ones right posterior temporal lobe without hemorrhage or mass effect.  5/1 Head MRA: Asymmetric decreased time-of-flight enhancement at the third order vessels in the left MCA distribution. Given the MRI findings, this is likely artifactual. CTA could be obtained if there is concern for additional infarct.  4/30 Blood Glucose 215, Creatinine 1.8, Troponin I was 0.42/0.32 with normal/no acute ischemia on EKG. BNP 218, Lactic Acid 3.2. Negative for COVID-19.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: J&J Dose 4/10/21 (1808980) COVID Positive 4/27/21  4/29/21: Presented to ED and admitted.  4/30/21: Pt. is a 49-year-old female with history of persistent asthma who was diagnosed with COVID-19- 5 days ago. The patient tested positive for COVID-19 infection on 04/25/2021.  Since then she had dry cough, on and off wheezing, worsening shortness of breath.  Since yesterday she became extremely short of breath for which she decided to come to the emergency room.  Earlier yesterday she was evaluated by an ED  physician and she was advised to be admitted because of hypoxemia and pulse oximetry of 87%. Patient declined admission and went home.  She came back with worsening shortness of breath.  On exam patient was comfortably breathing on 2 L with oxygen saturation 95% ; chest examination was significant for bilateral extensive rhonchi with good air entry and no wheezing.  Blood work shows sodium 133, potassium 2.4, BUN 5, creatinine 0.5, albumin 3.4, D-dimer was elevated at and follow-up with CT of the chest with contrast was done.  It showed bilateral extensive multilobar pneumonia .  There was no pulmonary thromboembolic disease.  5/4/21: Patient is a 49-year-old female who was diagnosed COVID positive on 4/25/2021.  She presented to the emergency department on 4/30/2021 with worsening shortness of breath and was noted to be hypoxic.  She was admitted to the medical floor with acute hypoxic respiratory failure, secondary to bilateral COVID-19 pneumonia.  She received 1 unit of convalescent plasma.  She was started on Rocephin, Zithromax, dexamethasone, and Remdesivir therapies.  She had a persistent dry cough for which codeine/guaifenesin was effective.  Her potassium was also noted to be low, and it was supplemented.  She was started on oral therapy and this has maintained it.  She is no longer requiring supplemental oxygen. She reports she is feeling much better. She has completed her Remdesivir therapy today and is requesting to go home.

Our office provided Moderna vaccines on May 12, 2021 to several County jail inmates with the assistance of Department.  While entering the vaccines in ImmTrac, there was one inmate who already had a first dose Pfizer vaccine that was administered on March 31, 2021 in Springs.  We notified the jail medical division to confirm with inmate about Pfizer vaccine administration in the event that it was a data entry error on ImmTrac.  Upon speaking with the inmate, he confirmed that he received the Pfizer vaccine in Springs before being incarcerated and was not aware that he needed to notify staff about prior vaccine administration.  Inmate did ask whether he would need to get a second dose of either vaccine.  As per Sheriff?s Medical Division, Doctor the jail?s medical director, advised him that since patient received Pfizer more than 30 days ago, there should be no issue with patient receiving Moderna yesterday and that patient could receive second dose of Moderna if they wanted to receive it.  As per Director of Nursing, ?The newest EUA allows a 1st dose of Pfizer to be completed with a 2nd dose Moderna. Additionally, the doses are with 42 days. This means he has completed the series now. I will forward you support documents later this afternoon, but no further steps are required.?  It was still recommended that a report be submitted.
Patient received second dose of Moderna prior to 28 days, or 24 (with 4 day grace period).

Patient in AAOA Vaccine clinic to receive J&J COVID Vaccine. States no previous allergic responses to vaccines or injectables, however does "pass out with lab draws or shots" but does fine afterwards. Vaccine provided at 0949. At 0950, patient became lightheaded and unresponsive, arms twitching and started gurgling. EMS activated. BP 100/60, HR 75, RR 30, hands cold and pulse ox not registering. Placed on O2 per FM. At 0951, patient was arousable. BP 102/60, HR 70, RR 26, pulse ox registering at 96%, no further body twitching. One touch blood sugar 72. From 0952-1000 VSS pulse ox 98%, patient awake, AAO, states she is cold. EMS arrived at 1000, history of events reviewed with EMS. Patient continues to be AAO, BO 149/82, HR 80, RR 18, Pulse Ox 100% . At 10:05, patient remains stable, EMS discussed with patient option of transport to local ER. Per EMS given previous h/o vasovagal response to injections, did not feel necessary to transport unless patient wished to go to ER (patient refused as she was feeling much better). Continued to monitor patient in AAOA vaccine clinic until 11:00. Patient provided apple juice and crackers. VSS BP 122/80 to 142/82, HR 60-64, RR 16-20, pulse ox 99-100% on RA. Stated she feels ok and wished to go home. Friend provided transport home and to stay with her today. Patient instructed to notify PMD of vasovagal response and to call EMS if needed.
PRIOR_VAX: All injections/blood draws

Immediately while receiving the injection I felt that the site very high, in fact it was injected into my left shoulder. I also immediately felt that the needle had to be forced harder than usual into my arm, - as if it was pushed through some tougher tissue than the typical muscle & soft tissue with shots. I could actually feel it forced through something like a membrane or cartilage into my shoulder.  I received the shot mid-afternoon & by late that evening my left arm was in severe pain from the shoulder down, so much so that it was very painful to just move my arm normally. This pain persisted for several days, I assumed this was a side effect from the flu vaccine that was mentioned as potentially occurring.  While the pain lessened somewhat over the following days, by 2 weeks later I realized that this was too long for a side effect & made an appointment to see a doctor for it.   I still had substantial pain & limited movement in my left arm a month later when I saw the Orthopedist  & now 9 months plus later I still have pain using my left arm in various normal day to day activities & simple movements.

From ED Note: 12 year old male with PMH of asthma on flovent, food allergies with epi-pen (has not required this) and pre-syncope/syncope who presents with concern for loss of consciousness and possible seizure-like activity following a COVID vaccine.   Mom notes that he was in his usual state of health when he presented to COVID clinic to get his first vaccine. He got the Pfizer vaccine, seconds after getting in his left arm, mom noted that he looked very "wide eyed" and distraught.  She notes that he slumped forward and had lost consciousness for approximately 5 seconds.  She noticed shaking movements in his right arm and bilateral lower legs.  She notes that his left arm was against her and therefore cannot comment on it.  She notes that his eyes were closed.  No tongue biting and no incontinence.  No secondary trauma.  She notes that when these 5 seconds were over he then had a period for about 30 minutes where he looked pale and was breathing heavy but was alert and answering questions.  She notes that he has had presyncopal episodes and episodes of feeling faint when getting flu shots in the past.  However, this time she noted that he had shaking which made her nervous for possible seizure activity.  Patient denies any chest pain or headache prior to the symptoms.  She came via ambulance for further evaluation.   On arrival, he reports that he feels 90% back to his baseline.  He notes that he does not feel quite ready to run around yet however denies any pains or discomforts, headache, weakness, numbness, or tingling.   He had eaten a full breakfast prior to getting the shot.  He had a normal night sleep and a normal day yesterday per mom.   Medical History: as above  Surgical history: none Family History: Reviewed and no pertinent related family hx pertaining to this visit Social History: Lives with family  Allergies: food allergies  Medications: flovent, epi-pen Immunizations: Up to date  Medical Decision Making  12 year old male with PMH of asthma on flovent, food allergies with epi-pen (has not required this) and pre-syncope/syncope who presents with concern for loss of consciousness and possible seizure-like activity following a COVID vaccine.  On arrival, he was alert, well-appearing, in no acute distress.  His vital signs were normal for age on room air.  His physical exam was very reassuring as above with a normal neurologic and cardiac evaluation.   Differential includes vasovagal/syncope in the setting of a known stressful trigger vs seizure given report of shaking in his extremities.  We feel the latter is significantly less likely given the timeline of the events.  Has no known seizure activity nor any triggers per history (fever, trauma, etc.).  He also has a normal neurologic assessment. At this time we will defer neurology consults given low concern for seizure.  It is possible that this represents a side effect of the vaccine however we also feel that this is less likely given the fact that his symptoms have been seconds after receiving the vaccine.  Nonetheless we reported the symptoms to the pharmacist who recorded it in the database.  We attained an EKG showing a known incomplete right bundle branch block (unchanged from 2013) and a slightly prolonged QTC of 477 (previously 451).    I encourage patient to stay well-hydrated, well rested in the setting of his suspected syncopal episode this morning.  I also suggested that for further vaccinations, that he lay down on the table and drink/eat well prior.  We provided strict return to ED criteria in the setting of worsening symptoms. All questions were answered at the time of discharge. Mom verbalized her understanding and agreement of the plan. He was discharged in a stable condition with mom at side.    **After patient was discharged, cardiology called the follow-up team due to the prolonged QTC to ensure that we were aware.  I contacted the patient's PCP to do a follow-up EKG in 1 month's time.
OTHER_MEDS: Albuterol MDI, Fluticasone 110 mcg, cetirizine 10 mg, EpiPen 0.3 mg PRN
PRIOR_VAX: influenza vaccine, presyncopal events

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received dose 1 of the Moderna COVID vaccine (lot 016C21A, exp 5/22/2021) at 1300. At 1305, patient's husband told EMT and PHN that the patient was not feeling well. Patient takes vitamins. Vital signs: O2 99%, pulse 70, respirations 12, blood pressure 114/72. At 1310, EMT and PHN monitored patient as she transferred unassisted from the chair in the observation area to the zero-gravity recliner laying down. Patient reported she had eaten breakfast and did not work out previous to coming. At 1315, vital signs O2 99%, pulse 57, respirations 12, blood pressure 112/74. PHN offered Benadryl but patient declined. PHN encouraged patient to follow up with her provider and when to contact 911. Patient reported feeling better with symptoms improved. Patient ate a cookie, drank water, both from the vaccine site, and her own Gatorade. Patient requested to sit up, EMT positioned the patient sitting up at 1325. Patient reported mild dizziness, tingling in her feet, difficulty focusing visually, nausea returned, and new left leg numbness. Vital signs: pulse 69, O2 99%, blood pressure 118/84, respirations 12. PHN encouraged patient to drink water. Patient reported having similar reactions when anxious in the past. Patient focused on breathing and meditation to ease anxiety. Patient reported wanting to leave, PHN encouraged patient to wait for 30min since start of symptoms. Patient declined. PHN encouraged patient to follow up with her provider and when to call ED. Patient's husband left to bring the car up to the front curb. EMT walked patient out to the car. patient left walking with steady gait at 1337.

I have also have been very forgetful and my mind is always cloudy.

My blood platelets were high.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Three hours after the second vaccine there was a soreness in my left arm, followed by a headache. The next day around 12:00pm, I started to experience swelling in my throat. The swelling made it difficult to breathe. About an hour later I experienced tightness in my chest, making it difficult to breathe again. I experienced shortness of breath and the tightening in my chest did not leave. I was able to make it more bearable by taking my inhaler, used for my asthma. Today (5/17), I am still experiencing tightness in my chest, although it is not as severe as it was yesterday. The swelling in my throat as disappeared today (5/17).
OTHER_MEDS: Montelukast for allergies, xhance nasal spray for allergies, sprintec for birth control.
ALLERGIES: Thought to have no allergies until second dose of vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was sitting in the post vaccination monitoring area after her 2nd dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on May 12. She was with her brother and another male. Pt came up to the hostess to let her know the patient was having a seizure. I was called to the waiting area. The patient was sitting with head hung down and hands were moving involuntarily. She was not responding  when calling her name. Her brother informed me that she does this at times and has a somatic seizure disorder. I asked how I could help and he asked that we get her outside in the fresh air. Got a wheel chair and by the time we started to put her in the wheel chair she was becoming more awake. We took her outside and she was more awake but tired. She told me that she did not do this with her 1st COVID vaccine but she has done after other vaccines.
OTHER_MEDS: Medication list was not updated at vaccine appointment.  She is not our patient so unsure of medication she is taking.
HISTORY: From Problem List in Epic (again, not our patient so not updated at this appointment): Sleeping difficulties Somatic symptom and related disorders Psychogenic nonepileptic seizure Generalized anxiety disorder Depression

SYMPTOM_TEXT: (DOB 06/10/1970) received the first dose of Pfizer with lot number EP7534 exp 03/20/2021 at 1530. At 1538 client walked to EMT station with her husband notifying EMT staff that client felt lightheaded and was moved to zero-gravity chair for closer monitoring. Client disclosed at 15:42 that she has been fasting since last night in anticipation for her colonoscopy the following day. Medical history was reviewed: heart problems, thyroid issues, cancer, and immunocompromised (Hashimoto). RN visually noted patient started having physical tremors, apple juice and water were offered to client by staff. No signs of respiratory compromise or itching/hives were noted. Vital signs at 1545: BP of 150/100, pulse of 76bpm, and 14 respirations per minute. Client reported feeling anxious and visibly wearing clothes with extremities exposed, RN staff discussed with husband getting jacket for client. Husband refused at this time, not wanting to leave as was actively providing emotional support to client. 1550 vital signs: BP of 140/90, pulse of 70bpm, and 14 irregular respirations per minute. Client refused oral nutrition interventions at this time in anticipation of colonoscopy. 1557 vital signs: BP of 140/90, pulse of 80bpm, and 16 respirations per minute. Patient accepted apple juice at this time. RN discussed with client if felt chilly, client stated just couldn't stop shaking, husband agreed to retrieve a jacket from the car. RN engaged with patient to provide distraction discussing what client had done prior in the day. Client remained alert and oriented x3 noting the gardening client had done prior to arriving for vaccination. 1606 vitals: BP of 150/100 and at this time client was offered EMS. Client agreed to having EMS called, EMS call was placed at 1606. 1610 EMS arrived with two paramedics and 1 EMT, client was moved into side hall for privacy and EMS assumed care of client. 1620 client left site to board the ambulance with her husband to take more tests on heart at a higher level of care, symptoms were not completely resolved. Client remained alert and oriented x3 on exit of site.
red, swollen, warm to the touch blotches
Family reported patient passed away in the evening.

Starting around 9:00pm with general malaise that developed into severe nausea and joint pain over next two hours. Pain was severe enough to bring tears. Began treating with Tylenol 650mg every 4-6hrs, which seemed to help initially. Starting around 11pm, I had severe chills with uncontrollable tremors lasting next 3-4hrs. Could not stop shaking, could not get warm. Intense joint pain continued. Was able to sleep intermittently from 2-3am, but awoke with return of severe nausea and vertigo/dizziness around 3am, accompanied by profuse sweating and hot flashes. I laid on cold tile floor with ice-pack on head/chest until it passed, about 30min, and nearly called for ambulance. Treated nausea by inhaling vapor from rubbing alcohol and taking a dose of zofran dissolving tab, which seemed to help. Able to sleep 4am-9am May 15th and return to normal diet. Malaise continued throughout 15th, but gradually subsided. Rashes in armpits and hot sweats night of 15th. I appear to be mostly normal as of today, May 17th.
OTHER_MEDS: Fish oil, vitamin D, creatine monohydrate, generic multivitamin
